Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.190 --> 00:00:02.320
FEMALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon.

00:00:02.320 --> 00:00:06.430
I'm delighted to welcome Chris
Kimball to Google.

00:00:06.430 --> 00:00:08.406
I'm sure he needs no
introduction, so I'm going to

00:00:08.406 --> 00:00:10.060
do a very brief one.

00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:12.610
He's the founder of "Cook's
Illustrated" magazine.

00:00:12.610 --> 00:00:14.950
It was founded back in 1980.

00:00:14.950 --> 00:00:17.240
And he's the host of "America's
Test Kitchen,"

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:22.020
which is the most watched
cooking show on public TV.

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:24.820
And he's made so many
contributions to the culinary

00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:27.430
industry that I'm not even going
to try to mention them.

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:31.770
But he did found Who's Who
and Cooking in America.

00:00:31.770 --> 00:00:36.730
And at least in my kitchen,
"America's Test Kitchen"

00:00:36.730 --> 00:00:38.640
cookbooks are a must have.

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:41.240
And Chris is here today to talk
about "The Science of

00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:44.050
Good Cooking." If you haven't
picked up your copy in the

00:00:44.050 --> 00:00:45.340
back, please do.

00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:50.200
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:51.015
CHRIS KIMBALL: It feels
like the "Johnny

00:00:51.015 --> 00:00:53.220
Carson Show" or something.

00:00:53.220 --> 00:00:55.250
So this is a little
bit about--

00:00:55.250 --> 00:00:57.375
I won't talk too much about the
book, but about what we do

00:00:57.375 --> 00:01:00.640
in "The Test Kitchen." You know,
the fundamental precept

00:01:00.640 --> 00:01:03.060
of science is you sit around
and think about why things

00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:06.220
happen, and then you devise an
experiment to either prove or

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:07.090
disprove that.

00:01:07.090 --> 00:01:10.070
So you watch the apple
fall, whatever.

00:01:10.070 --> 00:01:12.650
And the ultimate example
of this--

00:01:12.650 --> 00:01:14.470
there's a YouTube video
about this, actually.

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:15.670
It's about 40 minutes long.

00:01:15.670 --> 00:01:16.550
It's great.

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:20.340
A called Lawrence Krauss,
cosmologist, and he decided,

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.670
with a bunch of other
cosmologists a few years ago,

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:24.470
to figure out whether
we live in a closed,

00:01:24.470 --> 00:01:26.260
open, or flat universe.

00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:28.550
This will have something to do
with cooking, eventually.

00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:31.810
So in a closed universe, it
collapses, we have a big bang,

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:32.510
we all die.

00:01:32.510 --> 00:01:35.260
In open universe, it expands
exponentially.

00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:37.340
In a flat universe, it expands,
but the rate of

00:01:37.340 --> 00:01:38.780
expansion slows.

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:40.580
So they were trying to
figure out how to do

00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:42.300
that relatively simply.

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:44.870
And so the first thing they
said, well, OK, in a flat

00:01:44.870 --> 00:01:47.130
universe, light travels
in a straight line.

00:01:47.130 --> 00:01:50.590
In a closed or open universe,
light diverges or converges.

00:01:50.590 --> 00:01:53.180
Which means that if you looked
at something a long way from

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:56.630
Earth, it would be bigger or
smaller than it actually is.

00:01:56.630 --> 00:01:58.050
If you live in a flat
universe, it will

00:01:58.050 --> 00:01:59.500
be the right size.

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:02.280
OK, so the next thing
was what to measure.

00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:06.430
Well, they said, let's go as far
away from Earth as we can,

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:08.539
because the farther away we
are, the more we could see

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:11.280
that converging or diverging
of the light.

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:15.560
Let's go back to the Big Bang,
13.72 billion years ago.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:18.070
The problem with that is, for
about 100,000 years after the

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:20.150
Big Bang, it was like looking
at the center of the sun.

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:21.200
It was pea soup.

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:22.380
Couldn't see anything.

00:02:22.380 --> 00:02:25.770
So about 100,000 years later,
you could start to see things.

00:02:25.770 --> 00:02:29.040
And so, OK, that's
a good distance.

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:31.280
Now the question was, what
are you going to measure?

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:33.550
And here's where it got
a little weird.

00:02:33.550 --> 00:02:37.050
They said, well, the universe
is only 100,000 years old.

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:40.120
Nothing travels faster than
the speed of light.

00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:42.080
So that includes gravity.

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:44.310
Gravity can't travel faster
than the speed of light.

00:02:44.310 --> 00:02:47.440
So the biggest thing could be
100,000 light years, because

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:49.550
if you're a lump of matter,
you want to attract other

00:02:49.550 --> 00:02:53.210
matter, you couldn't communicate
farther than that.

00:02:53.210 --> 00:02:56.110
It's like a little town in
Germany 2,000 years ago, a

00:02:56.110 --> 00:03:00.250
village that maybe people from
20 or 30 miles might come in,

00:03:00.250 --> 00:03:02.430
but if you're 500 miles away,
you wouldn't even know the

00:03:02.430 --> 00:03:02.840
village existed.

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:03.630
Same thing.

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:06.460
So they said, OK, so the
object would be there.

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:08.560
We know where it's going
to be, how far away.

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:10.180
And it should be 100,000
light years.

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:14.030
That's the maximum size, which
turns out to be 1 degree of

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:16.580
360 in the sky.

00:03:16.580 --> 00:03:18.590
So the other question is,
how do you measure it?

00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:22.830
And they said, well, we'll
send up a balloon.

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:24.390
This is what I like, these
guys sit around trying to

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:25.690
figure out what kind
of universe.

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:28.440
They get this big helium
balloon, they send it up and

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:31.690
it has essentially a camera that
measures the background

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:34.050
microwave radiation
from that point.

00:03:34.050 --> 00:03:37.570
Light waves as they travel,
flatten out, infrared,

00:03:37.570 --> 00:03:39.540
microwaves have the longest
wavelength.

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:42.060
So for those of you-- and there
aren't many of you here.

00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:44.370
There's a few of my vintage--

00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:47.290
in the days a television station
stopped broadcasting,

00:03:47.290 --> 00:03:49.540
oddly enough, at 1:00 or 2:00
in the morning, you'd get

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:50.990
static on your television set.

00:03:50.990 --> 00:03:54.860
And 1% of that static was, in
fact, microwave radiation from

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:56.330
just after the Big Bang.

00:03:56.330 --> 00:03:58.260
So you could actually see it.

00:03:58.260 --> 00:04:03.100
So they took pictures, and they
developed it, and they

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:04.110
put it up on the wall.

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:07.180
And it turns out that the
biggest things they saw were

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:08.520
exactly 1 degree.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:10.640
And that was exactly
what was predicted.

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:13.760
And so since it was 1 degree,
we live in a flat universe.

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:16.991
So that's exactly what we do at
"America's Test Kitchen."

00:04:16.991 --> 00:04:19.940
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:04:19.940 --> 00:04:21.010
CHRIS KIMBALL: See?

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:23.140
On a slightly smaller scale.

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:25.040
So we don't have big balloons.

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:27.430
But we use scientific
principles.

00:04:27.430 --> 00:04:28.120
Equilibrium.

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:29.790
This was invented or discovered

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:32.470
about 1750 in France.

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:35.740
French scientists decided,
well, OK, I don't have

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:37.375
balloons, but I have
pig bladders.

00:04:37.375 --> 00:04:40.240
I'll fill it with alcohol, put
it in a big tub of water, and

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:41.130
I'll see what happens.

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:44.940
Well, of course, what happened
was water is 100% water,

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:48.570
alcohol is 50% water, so some of
the water from outside went

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:51.400
through the membrane to
create equilibrium.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.020
That's called osmosis.

00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:56.085
Diffusion.

00:04:56.085 --> 00:04:58.500
But if you're going to brine a
turkey next week, there's a

00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:00.330
little osmosis there.

00:05:00.330 --> 00:05:00.595
Salt.

00:05:00.595 --> 00:05:03.790
You put salt on the outside of
a turkey, or in a brine, and

00:05:03.790 --> 00:05:04.530
that's diffusion.

00:05:04.530 --> 00:05:06.870
The salt from the outside goes
to the inside to create

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:07.710
equilibrium.

00:05:07.710 --> 00:05:12.600
So when you brine, you're using
a very old scientific

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:14.420
concept of equilibrium.

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:17.650
And what happens is the chicken
or the turkey soaks up

00:05:17.650 --> 00:05:23.400
water, and if there was no
brine, there was no salt, that

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:25.280
water would come out
during cooking.

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:29.190
But what the salt does is it
takes the proteins, it

00:05:29.190 --> 00:05:33.370
denatures them, they are able
to now hold onto water,

00:05:33.370 --> 00:05:34.690
because there's now
room for water to

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:36.120
get into the proteins.

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:38.030
Some of the proteins turn
into a gelatin,

00:05:38.030 --> 00:05:39.380
which also absorb water.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:42.370
So what the salt does is help
the turkey hold onto water,

00:05:42.370 --> 00:05:44.150
even when heated and roasted.

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:45.660
So not all of it leaves.

00:05:45.660 --> 00:05:47.170
Some of it actually stays.

00:05:47.170 --> 00:05:50.040
And that's all based
on an old premise.

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:53.260
Some of the things we like
to do is disprove

00:05:53.260 --> 00:05:56.000
stupid cooking theories.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.140
The world is flat theories.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:01.430
One of them is sear meat
to seal in the juices.

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:05.110
You still in cookbooks today,
and on some cooking shows,

00:06:05.110 --> 00:06:07.500
will see people say that, and
it's just total nonsense.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:10.220
Searing meat sears meat.

00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:11.950
It's the Maillard
reaction, which

00:06:11.950 --> 00:06:13.250
we'll get to in a second.

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:15.830
Amino acids and sugars are
creating flavor compounds.

00:06:15.830 --> 00:06:19.140
But it turns out that juicy
meat is just a function of

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:20.610
internal temperature.

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:24.310
About 110 degrees, meat fibers
that sort of look like

00:06:24.310 --> 00:06:27.540
insulated wires will start to
shrink around the diameter and

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:28.600
the length.

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:31.830
The liquid in those fibers
gets pushed out.

00:06:31.830 --> 00:06:34.680
The more you cook meat, the
dryer it gets, and it has

00:06:34.680 --> 00:06:37.430
nothing to do with whether
it's seared or not.

00:06:37.430 --> 00:06:39.980
If you pot roast or barbecue,
and you start with a piece of

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:42.270
meat that has a lot of collagen
in it, like pork

00:06:42.270 --> 00:06:45.640
butt, for example, well, that
collagen turns into gelatin,

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:49.320
melts, and that will hold onto
liquid, so that does work over

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:51.230
a long period of time.

00:06:51.230 --> 00:06:56.880
Another thing people say very
often is braising turns out

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:59.440
moist, succulent meat.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:01.990
And it kind of makes sense,
because you have a closed pot,

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:03.970
and you have a little bit of
liquid, and you have a pot

00:07:03.970 --> 00:07:06.080
roast or piece of pork.

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:08.260
In fact, Madeleine Kamman, in
"The Making of a Cook," which

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:10.950
is a great book you should read,
says that very thing.

00:07:10.950 --> 00:07:12.620
She says the steam gets
into the meat.

00:07:12.620 --> 00:07:13.220
It does this.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:14.510
No.

00:07:14.510 --> 00:07:15.750
It's the same thing.

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:19.110
You can boil a pot roast, or
simmer a pot roast in water.

00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:20.530
You can roast it
in a dry oven.

00:07:20.530 --> 00:07:22.790
You can braise it in
a closed container.

00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:25.250
And if you get it to the same
internal temperature, 185,

00:07:25.250 --> 00:07:28.000
190, it will be exactly
the same inside.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.430
So it doesn't matter if there's
liquid around it, air

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:32.510
around it, a little bit of
liquid on it, steam, it

00:07:32.510 --> 00:07:33.500
doesn't matter.

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:35.880
It's all about the internal
temperature.

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:37.710
Lots of other things--

00:07:37.710 --> 00:07:43.860
recipes say pat meat dry
before you sautee it.

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:47.840
And, by the way, I know what
you all do, even though you

00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:48.470
work for Google.

00:07:48.470 --> 00:07:49.480
I know what you do.

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:52.870
And that is that you
take our recipes--

00:07:52.870 --> 00:07:54.450
and I do the same thing--

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:59.350
and you take them as vague
directions about what you

00:07:59.350 --> 00:08:02.030
might do if you actually
had the ingredients.

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:05.470
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:08:05.470 --> 00:08:08.670
CHRIS KIMBALL: And you don't,
and you don't have the right

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:09.720
cookware, and lots
of other things.

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.495
So our job is not to create
a recipe that

00:08:12.495 --> 00:08:13.340
works in our kitchen.

00:08:13.340 --> 00:08:15.520
It's for us to figure
out what you do.

00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:18.010
And what you do is really
interesting.

00:08:18.010 --> 00:08:20.960
And matter of fact, I think
behavioral psychology should

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:23.340
spend more time looking at--

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:24.810
they do, like, how
people vote.

00:08:24.810 --> 00:08:26.465
Now they should do
how people cook.

00:08:26.465 --> 00:08:29.520
About two years ago, we had a
chicken breast recipe, and we

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:30.510
sent our recipes out.

00:08:30.510 --> 00:08:33.400
It takes us five or six weeks
to develop a recipe.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:37.360
We sent it out to a bunch of you
who volunteered, and over

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:39.400
the course of a week, 200 or 300
of you will have made the

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:42.000
recipe, and you'll
fill out a form.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.810
And unless 80% of you say you
would make it again, we go

00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:46.080
back in the kitchen.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:48.130
Well, this particular
gentleman--

00:08:48.130 --> 00:08:50.290
and this recipe got
a great rating.

00:08:50.290 --> 00:08:52.250
90% of the people would
make it again.

00:08:52.250 --> 00:08:53.970
This one gentleman said it was
the worst chicken breast

00:08:53.970 --> 00:08:57.210
recipe he'd ever made, which
caught our attention.

00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:59.840
And at the bottom, there's a
little place on SurveyMonkey,

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:02.080
which is the software we use--

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:06.030
he had a comment, and this is
verbatim, what he said.

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:10.922
He said, "Well," comma, "I
didn't have any chicken."

00:09:10.922 --> 00:09:13.634
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:09:13.634 --> 00:09:15.650
CHRIS KIMBALL: OK.

00:09:15.650 --> 00:09:16.970
"I substituted shrimp."

00:09:16.970 --> 00:09:18.670
AUDIENCE: [GASPS]

00:09:18.670 --> 00:09:20.660
CHRIS KIMBALL: So if you cook
shrimp for 25 minutes, indeed,

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:24.280
it would be the worst shrimp
recipe you've ever had.

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:25.440
But it's my fault, see.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:29.160
So it was my job to say in the
head note, do not substitute

00:09:29.160 --> 00:09:33.220
shrimp for chicken in this
chicken breast recipe.

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:38.430
So anyway, to go back to the
steak story, so the problem

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:41.050
is, if you put a wet piece of
meat or poultry in a pan,

00:09:41.050 --> 00:09:43.820
assuming the pan is the right
temperature, the meat's not

00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:46.600
going to get above the boiling
point of water, because the

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:47.810
water has to evaporate first.

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:51.410
So your steak is sitting there
at 210 or 212 degrees until

00:09:51.410 --> 00:09:52.530
that water goes away.

00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:55.110
So you're steaming the meat,
it sticks to the pan.

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:58.190
The Maillard reaction, which as
I said is amino acids and

00:09:58.190 --> 00:10:00.150
sugars creating flavor
compounds, doesn't happen 'til

00:10:00.150 --> 00:10:03.150
over 300 degrees, so you're not
going to get any browning.

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:06.930
And that is a reason, by the
way, you shouldn't use

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:09.600
non-stick cookware-- because
70% of cookware sold in the

00:10:09.600 --> 00:10:10.760
United States is non-stick.

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:11.950
It's good for eggs,
it's good for

00:10:11.950 --> 00:10:13.590
seafood, a few other things.

00:10:13.590 --> 00:10:15.540
Stir fry with a sticky sauce.

00:10:15.540 --> 00:10:17.730
It's terrible for everything
else, because you can't create

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:21.200
a fond on the bottom of the
pan-- that brown stuff that

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:23.290
when you're first beginning to
cook, you throw away, because

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:26.480
it's messy, and then you realize
it has all the flavor.

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:29.290
Years ago, a friend of mine
came over from France--

00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:30.360
he was a butcher--

00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:32.790
to show us some tricks.

00:10:32.790 --> 00:10:36.360
And during the morning, he had a
bunch of onions, like 5 or 6

00:10:36.360 --> 00:10:37.990
pounds of onions, a little
wine, little

00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:39.970
water, little oil.

00:10:39.970 --> 00:10:44.510
All he did was put it in a big
Le Creuset Dutch oven, and he

00:10:44.510 --> 00:10:46.290
sauteed it, browned it,
caramelized it.

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:48.340
And every half hour or so, he
deglazed the bottom of the pot

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:49.840
with a little wine.

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:51.990
And he didn't add stock,
he didn't add any other

00:10:51.990 --> 00:10:52.950
ingredients.

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:58.380
And by 12:00, 12:30, we had
French onion soup, and it was

00:10:58.380 --> 00:10:59.940
the best French onion soup
I had in my life.

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:03.440
And all the flavor, 100% of it,
came from the fond at the

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:04.800
bottom of the pan.

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:08.020
And so if that had been a
non-stick pan, we would have

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:10.590
had the world's worst
French onion soup.

00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:11.290
So anyway.

00:11:11.290 --> 00:11:14.820
So those are just a few of
the things that we test.

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:17.710
And another one which is
relevant for next week, for

00:11:17.710 --> 00:11:21.400
those of you who are going to
make pie dough, recipes always

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:24.060
say add just enough water 'til
the dough holds together.

00:11:24.060 --> 00:11:27.740
Yeah, whoever wrote that should
be taken out and run

00:11:27.740 --> 00:11:31.000
over with a truck, because
you're all scared to add too

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.060
much water, so what happens?

00:11:33.060 --> 00:11:35.590
You create dry pie dough,
and it doesn't roll out.

00:11:35.590 --> 00:11:37.360
It rolls out into pieces, and
you have to do a pat in the

00:11:37.360 --> 00:11:40.270
pan crust when nobody's
looking.

00:11:40.270 --> 00:11:41.500
That's what's going to
happen, because I've

00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:43.370
done it many times.

00:11:43.370 --> 00:11:45.110
And the reason you don't want
to add too much water is

00:11:45.110 --> 00:11:47.275
because in flour, there
are two proteins--

00:11:47.275 --> 00:11:49.290
glutinin, which sounds like
gluten, but it's different,

00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:50.970
and gliadin.

00:11:50.970 --> 00:11:54.860
In the presence of water, they
form gluten, and that's why

00:11:54.860 --> 00:11:57.390
you could have a no knead bread
dough recipe-- because

00:11:57.390 --> 00:12:01.190
if you let water and flour sit
long enough, like overnight,

00:12:01.190 --> 00:12:02.660
gluten will develop
on its own.

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:03.970
You don't have to knead bread.

00:12:03.970 --> 00:12:06.900
So what's going on with pie
pastry is, a little too much

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:10.310
water, a little bit too much
gluten gets developed.

00:12:10.310 --> 00:12:13.550
So we sat around, just like
Lawrence Krauss did years ago,

00:12:13.550 --> 00:12:17.590
and said, we need more liquid,
but we can't use water,

00:12:17.590 --> 00:12:19.570
because water reacts with
glutinin and gliadin to

00:12:19.570 --> 00:12:20.280
produce gluten.

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:21.640
What else could we use?

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:23.700
And the obvious answer
was vodka.

00:12:23.700 --> 00:12:24.950
I mean, really.

00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:28.890
Because alcohol actually doesn't
react with proteins.

00:12:28.890 --> 00:12:29.780
Water does.

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:32.660
So we said, we'll use half
water, half vodka, add a

00:12:32.660 --> 00:12:34.910
little bit of extra liquid--
another tablespoon, so you

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:37.510
have a nice, moist dough,
rolls out easily.

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:40.290
And by the way, alcohol will
dissipate at a much lower

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:42.630
temperature than water, so you
put in the oven, and you end

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:46.200
up with a nice, dry, flaky
dough, so, vodka pie crust.

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:49.600
And thank you to our
food scientist.

00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:51.730
One thing I should warn you
about food scientists, because

00:12:51.730 --> 00:12:53.820
I've worked with them
all my life.

00:12:53.820 --> 00:12:55.840
We have a guy who works
with us, this guy,

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:57.820
Crosby, who's very good.

00:12:57.820 --> 00:13:00.790
But remember in fifth grade, you
had those stupid molecular

00:13:00.790 --> 00:13:03.350
things with the balls?

00:13:03.350 --> 00:13:08.770
Well, eventually, over time,
I kept asking, do molecules

00:13:08.770 --> 00:13:10.760
really look like this?

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:13.010
And some would say,
well, not really.

00:13:13.010 --> 00:13:14.802
It's just, we're trying to--

00:13:14.802 --> 00:13:17.380
I paraphrase--

00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:20.000
we're giving you as much
information as we think you

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.050
can handle.

00:13:22.050 --> 00:13:22.840
So great.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:23.640
They think I'm an idiot.

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:26.720
So over all these years, I'm
thinking about these red balls

00:13:26.720 --> 00:13:28.260
and green balls and
everything else.

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:32.210
And yes, it talks about
connectivity and other things,

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:34.880
but it is, in essence,
really, molecules

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:35.900
don't look like that.

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:39.030
So when you talk to a food
scientist, the first time you

00:13:39.030 --> 00:13:42.560
ask them a question about
starchy potatoes, for example,

00:13:42.560 --> 00:13:45.190
and amylose and amylopectin and
everything else, they'll

00:13:45.190 --> 00:13:48.850
give you the answer they think
you can handle, which is

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:50.830
basically the idiot's answer.

00:13:50.830 --> 00:13:52.960
And then you come back a couple
weeks later and say,

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:54.730
well, you know, it doesn't
really make sense because--

00:13:54.730 --> 00:13:56.700
and they say, OK, OK,
now I'll tell you.

00:13:56.700 --> 00:13:58.330
And then they give you
the next layer down.

00:13:58.330 --> 00:14:01.940
There's like 10 layers, and I'm
working my way down to the

00:14:01.940 --> 00:14:02.580
10th layer.

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:05.490
I'm at about layer 7 now,
because he thinks I can

00:14:05.490 --> 00:14:06.750
handle layer 7.

00:14:06.750 --> 00:14:09.710
But the problem with food
science is, as Einstein, of

00:14:09.710 --> 00:14:12.660
course, was not a food
scientist-- it was too hard--

00:14:12.660 --> 00:14:13.940
there are too many variables.

00:14:13.940 --> 00:14:15.550
There's too much
stuff going on.

00:14:15.550 --> 00:14:17.710
So it's very hard to
isolate one thing.

00:14:17.710 --> 00:14:20.690
Even if you isolate, let's say,
10% protein flour from

00:14:20.690 --> 00:14:24.560
12%, you do two cakes or two
biscuits, it could be that you

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:26.510
didn't measure something
properly, the ovens were

00:14:26.510 --> 00:14:30.820
slightly off, it was a humid
day versus not a humid day.

00:14:30.820 --> 00:14:33.570
So there's lots of stuff going
on, so you have to do things

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:36.200
over and over and over again to
make sure that your results

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:39.170
actually are reproducible,
which, of course, is the

00:14:39.170 --> 00:14:40.050
essence of science.

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:45.990
So that's what we do, and this
book is really a result of 20

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:47.880
years of work in the kitchen.

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:50.360
We took 50 scientific principles
in some recipes to

00:14:50.360 --> 00:14:52.390
illustrate them.

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:57.720
And I've been on tour, and one
of the things I do if it's a

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:02.980
morning show or something is we
have a red bliss potato, a

00:15:02.980 --> 00:15:05.340
non-starchy potato, and we
have a russet potato.

00:15:05.340 --> 00:15:09.670
The russet potato has more
starch, which has got a higher

00:15:09.670 --> 00:15:13.250
specific gravity, and should
sink, and the red bliss potato

00:15:13.250 --> 00:15:14.430
should float.

00:15:14.430 --> 00:15:16.670
And I did this on "The Today
Show" about a month ago, and

00:15:16.670 --> 00:15:17.940
they both sank.

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:21.220
So sometimes, the results
are not reproducible.

00:15:21.220 --> 00:15:23.905
So I just hid it behind
the other thing, and

00:15:23.905 --> 00:15:26.280
it just went on.

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:30.360
So that's what we do, and I'd
love to take some questions.

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:37.270
And by the way, before someone
has the courage to ask a

00:15:37.270 --> 00:15:40.310
question, Lynne Rossetto Casper
from "The Splendid

00:15:40.310 --> 00:15:44.530
Table," whom I've known for
a long time, she had this

00:15:44.530 --> 00:15:46.940
problem once, and she told the
audience that she would start

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:50.670
removing her clothes if she
didn't get a question asked.

00:15:50.670 --> 00:15:54.230
And they started asking
questions.

00:15:54.230 --> 00:15:55.370
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:56.910
So I was wondering two things.

00:15:56.910 --> 00:16:00.140
One of them is that you
mentioned caramelizing onions.

00:16:00.140 --> 00:16:02.640
And I know that what Einstein
told his cook-- that was one

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:03.880
of the author's pet peeves.

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:04.070
CHRIS KIMBALL: Yeah.

00:16:04.070 --> 00:16:05.880
AUDIENCE: That's a side thing.

00:16:05.880 --> 00:16:06.700
You can talk.

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:07.770
But the question I
have is actually

00:16:07.770 --> 00:16:08.610
about non-stick cookware.

00:16:08.610 --> 00:16:09.660
CHRIS KIMBALL: That
was Wolke, yeah.

00:16:09.660 --> 00:16:10.100
That guy.

00:16:10.100 --> 00:16:10.540
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:11.630
The question I have is actually

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:12.530
about non-stick cookware.

00:16:12.530 --> 00:16:15.680
There's actually new non-stick
cookware coming out.

00:16:15.680 --> 00:16:17.630
It's ceramic, I guess, base,
or something else.

00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:19.820
Can you talk a little bit about
what you think of those?

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:20.900
CHRIS KIMBALL: Yeah,
we've tested a lot

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:22.020
of non-stick cookware.

00:16:22.020 --> 00:16:25.140
There's low-stick cookware like
Calphalon, which, if you

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:27.270
look at it under a microscope,
it just has

00:16:27.270 --> 00:16:28.050
fewer craters in it.

00:16:28.050 --> 00:16:31.710
It's smoother, so the food
doesn't stick as much.

00:16:31.710 --> 00:16:35.010
There are ceramic non-stick
cookware as well.

00:16:35.010 --> 00:16:36.880
We basically didn't
like any of them.

00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:40.800
They either claimed they were
greener, which they really

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:43.070
weren't, or if they
really were green,

00:16:43.070 --> 00:16:44.730
they weren't non-stick.

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:47.270
So we went through all of them,
and the one that we

00:16:47.270 --> 00:16:49.010
ended up with is just
the classic.

00:16:49.010 --> 00:16:51.050
They all use essentially the
same chemical-- slightly

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:52.690
different bonding techniques.

00:16:52.690 --> 00:16:54.130
The problem with non-stick
cookware--

00:16:54.130 --> 00:16:55.270
there's a number of them--

00:16:55.270 --> 00:16:57.690
first of all, there's something
called polymer fume

00:16:57.690 --> 00:17:01.570
fever, and I actually subjected
myself to this just

00:17:01.570 --> 00:17:02.560
to find out what it was like.

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:09.619
So over 500 degrees, you'll see
the smoking, and if you

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:11.970
happen to have a parakeet in
the room, you know, the

00:17:11.970 --> 00:17:14.359
parakeet might not survive
that process.

00:17:14.359 --> 00:17:16.780
I took a big whiff, and had a
vicious headache for about

00:17:16.780 --> 00:17:17.730
five hours.

00:17:17.730 --> 00:17:20.000
Over 600 degrees, that chemical
actually starts to

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.150
break down, and that's
why non-stick pans,

00:17:22.150 --> 00:17:23.060
over a year or two--

00:17:23.060 --> 00:17:26.190
I mean, in our kitchen, they
don't last more than a year.

00:17:26.190 --> 00:17:29.130
They actually start to break
down, and that coating

00:17:29.130 --> 00:17:30.360
actually comes off.

00:17:30.360 --> 00:17:34.840
So the other thing you can use
is cast iron, if you are of

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:37.280
the mind to season it properly,
which takes a little

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:39.760
more time, which I like.

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:43.190
But when it comes to doing
scrambled eggs, a 10-inch or

00:17:43.190 --> 00:17:46.330
8-inch non-stick All-Clad or
something similar actually is

00:17:46.330 --> 00:17:46.905
fairly essential.

00:17:46.905 --> 00:17:50.270
But that's about all
I use it for.

00:17:50.270 --> 00:17:52.860
AUDIENCE: I'll say in defense of
non-stick, you guys have a

00:17:52.860 --> 00:17:57.090
great recipe from a few months
ago for Thai stir fried

00:17:57.090 --> 00:18:00.650
noodles for which you say
specifically, get this

00:18:00.650 --> 00:18:03.600
non-stick 12-inch pan.

00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:05.160
Great recipe, I love it.

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:08.610
One of the great examples of
I don't do it unless I have

00:18:08.610 --> 00:18:10.040
exactly what "Cook's
Illustrated"

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:12.950
says I need to have.

00:18:12.950 --> 00:18:16.456
CHRIS KIMBALL: You're the
only reader who does.

00:18:16.456 --> 00:18:17.980
I've finally found him.

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:18.745
AUDIENCE: From bitter
experience,

00:18:18.745 --> 00:18:20.110
I've learned my lesson.

00:18:20.110 --> 00:18:23.430
So my question-- you guys test
all these recipes over and

00:18:23.430 --> 00:18:25.680
over again in the "Test
Kitchen." What do you do with

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:27.440
all the food that you create?

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:30.220
CHRIS KIMBALL: Oh, well, first
of all, we're not licensed by

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:33.355
the town of Brookline just
outside of Boston to serve

00:18:33.355 --> 00:18:35.280
food to the public.

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:35.860
It's a long story.

00:18:35.860 --> 00:18:40.460
So we wanted to give food to the
local shelter, food bank.

00:18:40.460 --> 00:18:44.020
We do give canned food, but we
couldn't give our cooked food.

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:47.060
So we have about 140 employees,
slightly smaller

00:18:47.060 --> 00:18:51.030
than you, and the test cooks in
the kitchen-- we have about

00:18:51.030 --> 00:18:54.570
45 test cooks, it's about a
3,500 square foot kitchen--

00:18:54.570 --> 00:18:58.740
the really good food, and the
really expensive food, like

00:18:58.740 --> 00:19:01.330
the tenderloin, the lobster,
et cetera--

00:19:01.330 --> 00:19:02.920
that immediately disappears.

00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:06.710
We have these big clear plastic
takeout containers and

00:19:06.710 --> 00:19:08.050
big magic markers.

00:19:08.050 --> 00:19:08.930
So I--

00:19:08.930 --> 00:19:12.240
Chris, for Chris, put the stuff
in, and go into our

00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:12.690
takeout fridge.

00:19:12.690 --> 00:19:15.040
And at night, they
bring it home.

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:19.950
The food that's pretty good
but not great, we call the

00:19:19.950 --> 00:19:21.880
marketing department
down for that.

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:23.195
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:19:23.195 --> 00:19:26.540
CHRIS KIMBALL: No, I mean,
