00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:55.720
been cooking all day, and they
just take the food home, so.

00:19:55.720 --> 00:20:00.000
AUDIENCE: You brought up the
concept of brining earlier,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.870
and the best Thanksgiving turkey
I ever made I brined.

00:20:04.870 --> 00:20:07.650
And could you go over some of
the basic principles, since a

00:20:07.650 --> 00:20:10.380
lot of people are going to be
roasting turkeys next week, of

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:12.960
what it takes to make
a good turkey?

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:14.580
CHRIS KIMBALL: Yes.

00:20:14.580 --> 00:20:17.140
The problem with having a food
magazine is every year,

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:18.650
there's Thanksgiving,
and we have to come

00:20:18.650 --> 00:20:19.990
up with a new recipe.

00:20:19.990 --> 00:20:23.570
So somehow we've come
up with 20 versions.

00:20:23.570 --> 00:20:25.870
The basic formula is
1 cup of table salt

00:20:25.870 --> 00:20:27.200
per gallon of water.

00:20:27.200 --> 00:20:30.880
If it's going to be a 12, 14
pound turkey, you'd brine it

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:33.180
for six to eight hours,

00:20:33.180 --> 00:20:35.080
something like that, overnight.

00:20:35.080 --> 00:20:37.650
You got to keep it cool,
preferably no more than 40

00:20:37.650 --> 00:20:41.190
degrees, which can be a problem
if you don't have a

00:20:41.190 --> 00:20:43.760
cold cellar somewhere
or outside.

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:47.860
And then you want to make sure
it's dried off very well.

00:20:47.860 --> 00:20:53.255
You put it in a 375 to 400 oven,
breast side down for an

00:20:53.255 --> 00:20:56.440
hour, then flip it breast side
up and continue cooking it--

00:20:56.440 --> 00:20:58.660
maybe even increase the
temperature for the last half

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:01.300
hour or so.

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:03.540
We've done lots of other
recipes, one of which I like

00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:06.400
is you cut it into parts
and you braise it.

00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:07.980
I did that last year.

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:10.730
Then you get a great gravy out
of it, and then you don't have

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:12.360
the problem with the white meat,
dark meat, when it's

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:13.940
done problem.

00:21:13.940 --> 00:21:16.830
I just did for "Morning
Edition" next week on

00:21:16.830 --> 00:21:19.750
Wednesday-- we do a segment
every year on Thanksgiving,

00:21:19.750 --> 00:21:21.900
and we did Julia Child recipes,

00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:23.580
all Julia Child recipes.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:26.890
She's got this great recipe
where she takes the backbone

00:21:26.890 --> 00:21:30.330
out and takes the whole breast
and puts it over a huge amount

00:21:30.330 --> 00:21:34.820
of stuffing on a roasting tray
with aluminum foil, cooks

00:21:34.820 --> 00:21:38.470
that, and then she has the thigh
and the legs together,

00:21:38.470 --> 00:21:41.240
those two pieces roasted
separately on a rack on a

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:42.640
baking sheet.

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:44.300
But what she does is
really interesting.

00:21:44.300 --> 00:21:46.340
She takes the bone out
of the thigh, which

00:21:46.340 --> 00:21:47.070
takes about a minute.

00:21:47.070 --> 00:21:48.070
It's real easy to do.

00:21:48.070 --> 00:21:49.440
Just use a paring knife.

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:52.940
And then she spreads it open,
puts salt, pepper, a little

00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:56.180
sage, whatever you want, sewed
it up, or just wrapped it

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:58.110
easily with some string
and roasted that.

00:21:58.110 --> 00:21:59.850
Only took about an hour
and a half to cook.

00:21:59.850 --> 00:22:02.470
And then when you slice
the thigh, there's no

00:22:02.470 --> 00:22:04.530
bone, which is great.

00:22:04.530 --> 00:22:06.000
And that really works well.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:09.070
And if you like, she also had a
picture of reassembling the

00:22:09.070 --> 00:22:11.750
bird after it's cooked, so you
have that little Norman

00:22:11.750 --> 00:22:13.590
Rockwell moment or whatever.

00:22:13.590 --> 00:22:15.220
If anyone does have
that moment.

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:17.170
So that's the basic concept.

00:22:17.170 --> 00:22:19.470
The other way you can
do it is butterfly a

00:22:19.470 --> 00:22:21.020
turkey after brining.

00:22:21.020 --> 00:22:22.470
You take the backbone out.

00:22:22.470 --> 00:22:23.990
It's good to have poultry
shears for that.

00:22:23.990 --> 00:22:27.400
Flatten it, press down on the
breastbone, and then cook that

00:22:27.400 --> 00:22:31.280
on a rack over a huge mound of
stuffing, which is also one of

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:32.230
my favorite techniques.

00:22:32.230 --> 00:22:34.590
So you don't have to worry about
a little bit of stuffing

00:22:34.590 --> 00:22:37.810
in the cavity, which you should
never do, because the

00:22:37.810 --> 00:22:40.020
stuffing takes a long time
to get up to 160.

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:43.070
You don't have much of it, and
the meat will be overcooked.

00:22:43.070 --> 00:22:46.110
So butterfly it, take the
backbone out, rack over

00:22:46.110 --> 00:22:48.930
stuffing, and you get
maximum stuffing.

00:22:48.930 --> 00:22:51.030
So those are four suggestions.

00:22:53.570 --> 00:22:54.860
AUDIENCE: Did you start
as a food writer?

00:22:54.860 --> 00:22:56.870
Was that what you sort of--

00:22:56.870 --> 00:22:58.900
CHRIS KIMBALL: I started as
a primitive art major at

00:22:58.900 --> 00:23:02.050
Columbia in 1969.

00:23:02.050 --> 00:23:02.690
Well, actually, no.

00:23:02.690 --> 00:23:05.950
I had four years of the
revolution, so we didn't have

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:09.610
finals three out of the four
years, because the secret was,

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:13.210
we only had revolutions
when it was warm,

00:23:13.210 --> 00:23:15.140
which was in May, usually.

00:23:15.140 --> 00:23:16.460
So I started that.

00:23:16.460 --> 00:23:20.020
I worked in a small publishing
firm in New York for a couple

00:23:20.020 --> 00:23:24.340
years, ran a company for a
few years in the '70s.

00:23:24.340 --> 00:23:26.660
It was in and around the whole
issue of magazines and

00:23:26.660 --> 00:23:27.630
publishing.

00:23:27.630 --> 00:23:30.650
And then I started "Cook's"
in 1980--

00:23:30.650 --> 00:23:33.020
April 1980.

00:23:33.020 --> 00:23:34.340
Today, if you want to--

00:23:34.340 --> 00:23:36.390
I've been grandfathered
into my own company.

00:23:36.390 --> 00:23:39.290
I don't think I'd get a job
there now, probably.

00:23:39.290 --> 00:23:42.310
If you wanted to get a job in
our kitchen today, you'd have

00:23:42.310 --> 00:23:45.460
to come in and do a bench test,
which means that a bunch

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:47.500
of people will stand around you
with clipboards and not

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:51.540
talk while you cook all day, to
see if you have the knife

00:23:51.540 --> 00:23:53.260
skills, you can expedite.

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:56.880
But really, we're looking for
people who are incredibly

00:23:56.880 --> 00:24:00.970
stubborn, don't mind doing the
same thing constantly, like

00:24:00.970 --> 00:24:03.400
the same recipe for weeks
and weeks on end.

00:24:03.400 --> 00:24:05.720
You have to develop a recipe
on your own and write it up

00:24:05.720 --> 00:24:07.490
and submit the article.

00:24:07.490 --> 00:24:12.910
And then we do three month
internships, and then usually

00:24:12.910 --> 00:24:14.820
at the end of that period, we'll
keep one or two of the

00:24:14.820 --> 00:24:19.340
people to work full time
in the kitchen.

00:24:19.340 --> 00:24:22.130
So what we really do
is a group process.

00:24:22.130 --> 00:24:25.140
We sit down every Tuesday
morning at 9:00 AM, editorial

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:29.400
table, and whoever's working on
a particular recipe talks.

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:31.210
We sit down, have ideas.

00:24:31.210 --> 00:24:32.870
Every time there's a tasting,
there's a bunch of people in

00:24:32.870 --> 00:24:33.370
the kitchen.

00:24:33.370 --> 00:24:36.400
So it's really very much
about a group process.

00:24:36.400 --> 00:24:40.000
It's not quite one man, one
vote, but it's almost that.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.770
And that's how we develop
the process.

00:24:42.770 --> 00:24:44.606
It comes from--

00:24:44.606 --> 00:24:48.940
I went to a high school which
used an oval table, the

00:24:48.940 --> 00:24:49.860
Harkness table.

00:24:49.860 --> 00:24:52.650
And you'd sit around a table,
and the professor or teacher

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:55.870
would be standing up in the
corner, and you would have to

00:24:55.870 --> 00:24:58.110
come up with a position about
something about Russian

00:24:58.110 --> 00:25:00.700
history, and you'd have to
defend your position as your

00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:03.700
fellow students ripped you to
shreds, which is basically

00:25:03.700 --> 00:25:06.590
what we do now is to sit around
and argue, which I

00:25:06.590 --> 00:25:09.240
assume you do a lot here, too.

00:25:09.240 --> 00:25:11.010
AUDIENCE: So you're in
magazines, but you must also

00:25:11.010 --> 00:25:12.380
have been kind of crazy
about food.

00:25:12.380 --> 00:25:14.765
And then you also seem to have
this scientific bent.

00:25:14.765 --> 00:25:16.410
CHRIS KIMBALL: Well, I've been
cooking since I was about

00:25:16.410 --> 00:25:17.460
seven, yes.

00:25:17.460 --> 00:25:19.910
My first recipe was a chocolate
cake out of "The Joy

00:25:19.910 --> 00:25:23.280
of Cooking" with a seven minute
boiled icing, which

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:25.130
turned out like snot.

00:25:25.130 --> 00:25:27.635
Actually, I do still
remember the cake.

00:25:27.635 --> 00:25:31.560
Everyone said it was very good,
but I knew it wasn't.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:34.690
And in the '70s, I
started taking a

00:25:34.690 --> 00:25:36.190
lot of cooking classes.

00:25:36.190 --> 00:25:40.050
And I realized there was one
guy in particular, who was

00:25:40.050 --> 00:25:42.120
actually a great guy,
but he put on

00:25:42.120 --> 00:25:43.400
this fake French accent--

00:25:43.400 --> 00:25:44.940
he was from Florida.

00:25:44.940 --> 00:25:47.580
But he talked like
the [FAKE FRENCH]

00:25:47.580 --> 00:25:50.570
like this, and he would say
things like you have to scald

00:25:50.570 --> 00:25:52.670
milk to make a bechamel.

00:25:52.670 --> 00:25:56.460
Well, I went home, made it with
cold milk, it was fine.

00:25:56.460 --> 00:25:57.890
He refused to talk about it.

00:25:57.890 --> 00:26:00.020
And it turns out that you only
scald milk if it's raw milk,

00:26:00.020 --> 00:26:03.660
because pasteurization is
scalding milk, and you want to

00:26:03.660 --> 00:26:05.450
kill off an enzyme
that needs to be

00:26:05.450 --> 00:26:07.100
killed to have it thicken.

00:26:07.100 --> 00:26:11.270
So it occurred to me, the
emperor's new clothes, that a

00:26:11.270 --> 00:26:13.340
lot of stuff that was being
taught at the time in the '60s

00:26:13.340 --> 00:26:16.050
and '70s was just being
passed down.

00:26:16.050 --> 00:26:18.470
And probably at the time, it
made sense, like when people

00:26:18.470 --> 00:26:19.780
had nothing but raw milk.

00:26:19.780 --> 00:26:21.290
But there was a whole bunch of
things like that that just

00:26:21.290 --> 00:26:22.400
made no sense anymore.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:25.450
And the cookware was changing,
the food processor came in

00:26:25.450 --> 00:26:28.150
from Carl Sontheimer
in the early '70s.

00:26:28.150 --> 00:26:31.130
French cooking was going
away, American

00:26:31.130 --> 00:26:33.180
cooking was coming up.

00:26:33.180 --> 00:26:37.662
So my interest was actually
starting a magazine where you

00:26:37.662 --> 00:26:38.860
could talk about cooking.

00:26:38.860 --> 00:26:41.570
At the time, there was
"Cuisine," "Food &amp; Wine," "Bon

00:26:41.570 --> 00:26:43.000
Apetitt," "Gourmet," none
of which really

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:43.890
focused on the kitchen.

00:26:43.890 --> 00:26:46.920
It was all about people
smiling at parties,

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:48.890
traveling, on yachts.

00:26:48.890 --> 00:26:51.455
And so I just wanted to focus
on fudgy brownies,

00:26:51.455 --> 00:26:53.800
essentially.

00:26:53.800 --> 00:26:56.280
AUDIENCE: So you talked about
techniques, but I want to ask

00:26:56.280 --> 00:26:59.590
you about the actual product
and ingredients.

00:26:59.590 --> 00:27:04.020
I made a conscious decision to
switch to grass-fed beef, and

00:27:04.020 --> 00:27:06.940
most of these techniques no
longer work, because this meat

00:27:06.940 --> 00:27:07.790
is so different.

00:27:07.790 --> 00:27:09.490
There's less fat.

00:27:09.490 --> 00:27:11.307
What recommendations,
what suggestions do

00:27:11.307 --> 00:27:12.630
you have for me?

00:27:12.630 --> 00:27:14.890
CHRIS KIMBALL: Well, we raise
our own beef and pork, too,

00:27:14.890 --> 00:27:18.130
and we started out doing
pure grass fed.

00:27:18.130 --> 00:27:22.790
Well, I don't know if you've
ever had no grain purely grass

00:27:22.790 --> 00:27:25.100
fed, but it's tough
and it's strong.

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:27.350
And actually, in the last
three months, we

00:27:27.350 --> 00:27:28.840
grained them, too.

00:27:28.840 --> 00:27:32.630
So I like mostly grass fed, but
I like grain at the end,

00:27:32.630 --> 00:27:33.870
because I think it's better.

00:27:33.870 --> 00:27:35.640
But it's like trying
to cook venison,

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:37.910
because it's very lean.

00:27:37.910 --> 00:27:43.350
And the other problem is the
butchers love the round, the

00:27:43.350 --> 00:27:46.060
thigh, because it's this huge
hunk of meat with just one

00:27:46.060 --> 00:27:47.730
bone in it.

00:27:47.730 --> 00:27:49.375
It's not complicated.

00:27:49.375 --> 00:27:51.580
But the problem is, it's lean.

00:27:51.580 --> 00:27:53.160
And especially grass-fed beef.

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:56.340
So the first thing I would do
is get the fattiest cuts.

00:27:56.340 --> 00:27:58.350
Chuck eye roast,
shoulder roast,

00:27:58.350 --> 00:27:59.200
anything from the chuck.

00:27:59.200 --> 00:28:02.650
I would never touch the round
under any circumstances.

00:28:02.650 --> 00:28:07.810
And then, unless you want to
lard it, like Fannie Farmer

00:28:07.810 --> 00:28:09.520
used to do, you're probably
going to have to

00:28:09.520 --> 00:28:11.360
cook it low and slow.

00:28:11.360 --> 00:28:15.380
But I would get the fattiest cut
from grass-fed beef that I

00:28:15.380 --> 00:28:16.770
possibly could.

00:28:16.770 --> 00:28:18.250
Don't get anything lean,
because it's

00:28:18.250 --> 00:28:20.970
going to be lean anyway.

00:28:20.970 --> 00:28:23.100
AUDIENCE: I'm curious what your
take is on the molecular

00:28:23.100 --> 00:28:25.620
gastronomy movement, which also
sort of bills itself as a

00:28:25.620 --> 00:28:26.950
science driven, although
probably not

00:28:26.950 --> 00:28:29.130
as accessible, approach.

00:28:29.130 --> 00:28:31.400
CHRIS KIMBALL: Well, I'm now an
instant expert, because I

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:35.600
went to see Nathan Myhrvold two
days ago, and his chefs

00:28:35.600 --> 00:28:39.550
cooked me a 12-course meal
one afternoon in Seattle.

00:28:39.550 --> 00:28:45.530
And first of all, OK,
let me describe.

00:28:45.530 --> 00:28:47.660
He has a lab to do a lot
of other things.

00:28:47.660 --> 00:28:50.260
The modernist cuisine is
just a small subset.

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:50.760
You walk in.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:52.150
The place is huge.

00:28:52.150 --> 00:28:56.250
It must have 50 $1 million
machines in there to do all

00:28:56.250 --> 00:29:00.280
sorts of weird things, like
3D printers and stuff.

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:05.920
So the first thing I walk in is
I see this big HD screen,

00:29:05.920 --> 00:29:08.720
and things are popping
on and off.

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:09.470
And I say, what's that?

00:29:09.470 --> 00:29:12.900
He said, well, a few years ago,
we decided to solve the

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:14.866
problem of malaria.

00:29:14.866 --> 00:29:16.120
OK.

00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:18.270
And one of the guys on the team
was one of the guys who

00:29:18.270 --> 00:29:21.840
helped develop the Star Wars
project, which actually was

00:29:21.840 --> 00:29:23.900
pretty much a failure,
as far as I can tell.

00:29:23.900 --> 00:29:25.190
And he said, well, I don't
know, just get a

00:29:25.190 --> 00:29:26.780
laser gun and zap them.

00:29:26.780 --> 00:29:30.370
And then the guy said to me,
well, at first we thought that

00:29:30.370 --> 00:29:32.390
was foolish, comma.

00:29:32.390 --> 00:29:33.800
I said, what do you
mean "at first"?

00:29:33.800 --> 00:29:35.730
It's like, what, it's
not foolish now?

00:29:35.730 --> 00:29:37.570
So he claims--

00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:41.270
I didn't believe this-- he
claims that this thing was

00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:45.560
actually showing there's
mosquitoes in a glass--

00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:48.950
am I losing my voice here?

00:29:48.950 --> 00:29:49.270
Hello?

00:29:49.270 --> 00:29:51.060
There we are.

00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:54.645
He claims that he had this big
glass container, an aquarium

00:29:54.645 --> 00:29:58.620
of mosquitoes, and they could
sense the mosquitoes

00:29:58.620 --> 00:29:59.080
individually.

00:29:59.080 --> 00:30:01.350
That's what was showing
up on the screen.

00:30:01.350 --> 00:30:02.350
Then it gets weird.

00:30:02.350 --> 00:30:04.810
It says, they can tell the
difference between a male

00:30:04.810 --> 00:30:06.990
mosquito and a female
mosquito.

00:30:06.990 --> 00:30:08.750
And I said, how do
you do that?

00:30:08.750 --> 00:30:10.520
He said, well, female mosquitoes
beat their wings at

00:30:10.520 --> 00:30:12.360
a different RPM than
male mosquitoes.

00:30:12.360 --> 00:30:13.470
OK.

00:30:13.470 --> 00:30:15.840
Female mosquitoes bite,
males don't.

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:17.110
So I said, then what happens?

00:30:17.110 --> 00:30:19.050
He said, oh, then the laser gun
melts their wings and they

00:30:19.050 --> 00:30:21.000
fall down and die.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:27.600
I said, OK, so you're in Africa,
Niger, and you have

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:30.390
this $100,000 mosquito
killing laser gun.

00:30:30.390 --> 00:30:31.450
Now what are you going to do?

00:30:31.450 --> 00:30:33.610
Well, we'd ring the
village with them.

00:30:33.610 --> 00:30:37.380
I said, how about like, $1.00
for a mosquito net?

00:30:37.380 --> 00:30:39.610
Like, really?

00:30:39.610 --> 00:30:42.330
Anyway, so I was going,
like, really?

00:30:42.330 --> 00:30:45.910
So anyway, the meal was
fabulous, though.

00:30:45.910 --> 00:30:47.750
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:30:47.750 --> 00:30:50.960
CHRIS KIMBALL: And there were
no mosquitoes anywhere.

00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:57.210
I mean, he's proven if you're
incredibly smart, and you have

00:30:57.210 --> 00:31:00.480
unlimited capital and time,
what you can do to food.

00:31:00.480 --> 00:31:02.850
It has no bearing on home
cooking at all.

00:31:02.850 --> 00:31:05.460
But, I mean, for example,
the pistachio gelato--

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:07.220
I love pistachio gelato.

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:08.690
I've had it in a lot of
different places.

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:10.550
And most of the time, it's
vanilla ice cream with green

00:31:10.550 --> 00:31:12.280
food coloring, essentially,
because it doesn't taste like

00:31:12.280 --> 00:31:13.360
pistachio, right?

00:31:13.360 --> 00:31:16.035
So this pistachio gelato
was amazing.

00:31:16.035 --> 00:31:19.240
I mean, it's like, amazing
pistachio flavor.

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:22.620
And he extracted oil,
and guess what.

00:31:22.620 --> 00:31:25.120
Each scoop, which is about this
big, was $25 worth of

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:28.300
pistachios to get one scoop
of pistachio gelato.

00:31:28.300 --> 00:31:30.240
The other thing he showed
me-- and they were

00:31:30.240 --> 00:31:31.430
great French fries--

00:31:31.430 --> 00:31:35.350
but in order to get that crunchy
outside, he puts the

00:31:35.350 --> 00:31:37.440
French fries in water--

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:40.590
am I losing my voice again?

00:31:40.590 --> 00:31:44.680
I think you have to keep putting
quarters in the thing.

00:31:44.680 --> 00:31:47.270
It's a cavitation device,
essentially.

00:31:47.270 --> 00:31:50.340
Sonic waves go through the water
and rough up the surface

00:31:50.340 --> 00:31:51.740
of the potato.

00:31:51.740 --> 00:31:54.530
And so, yeah, it did
work, but he's

00:31:54.530 --> 00:31:55.750
extracting maximum flavor.

00:31:55.750 --> 00:31:59.160
So the answer is, why not?

00:31:59.160 --> 00:31:59.900
Good for him.

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:00.800
He's an interesting guy.

00:32:00.800 --> 00:32:01.740
He's rich.

00:32:01.740 --> 00:32:03.860
The food was great.

00:32:03.860 --> 00:32:06.840
But I don't think anybody here
is going to be making $25 a

00:32:06.840 --> 00:32:08.970
scoop pistachio ice cream
anytime soon.

00:32:08.970 --> 00:32:11.590
Although maybe some of those
techniques end up in a home

00:32:11.590 --> 00:32:12.380
kitchen in 10 years.

00:32:12.380 --> 00:32:13.060
I don't know.

00:32:13.060 --> 00:32:14.200
But it's not what we do.

00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:20.260
What we do is, my premise has
been, most people most of the

00:32:20.260 --> 00:32:23.650
time don't have a lot of
success in the kitchen.

00:32:23.650 --> 00:32:25.387
It's not necessarily a failure,
but it doesn't turn

00:32:25.387 --> 00:32:27.120
out exactly the way you want.

00:32:27.120 --> 00:32:30.820
If you were building airplanes,
and 80% of the

00:32:30.820 --> 00:32:33.150
time, they fell out of the
sky, you wouldn't be in

00:32:33.150 --> 00:32:34.370
business too long.

00:32:34.370 --> 00:32:36.990
Recipes, if you think of it as
a business, it's the only

00:32:36.990 --> 00:32:39.230
business in the world where you
can actually have a very

00:32:39.230 --> 00:32:41.570
high failure rate and
still be around.

00:32:41.570 --> 00:32:44.720
And so our thought was, we're
not trying to get you to

00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:46.840
modernist cuisine or
French Laundry.

00:32:46.840 --> 00:32:48.620
We're just trying to get people
to the point where most

00:32:48.620 --> 00:32:50.530
of the time they go in
the kitchen, if they

00:32:50.530 --> 00:32:51.750
do follow the recipe--

00:32:51.750 --> 00:32:55.150
don't substitute shrimp
for chicken--

00:32:55.150 --> 00:32:56.970
it'll turn out well.

00:32:56.970 --> 00:32:58.460
And that's all.

00:32:58.460 --> 00:33:00.290
We're not trying to
create chefs.

00:33:00.290 --> 00:33:02.680
We're just trying to say, you
can be confident, go in the

00:33:02.680 --> 00:33:05.320
kitchen, and get pretty
good results.

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:07.240
That's about it.

00:33:07.240 --> 00:33:08.010
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:33:08.010 --> 00:33:11.230
For a variety of reasons, my
girlfriend and I only get to

00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:12.540
cook it once a week or so.

00:33:12.540 --> 00:33:17.180
Do you have any advice for
rewarding but efficient

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:19.900
occasional cooking
at small scale?

00:33:19.900 --> 00:33:24.260
CHRIS KIMBALL: Yeah, the best
thing I can say is, 100 years

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:29.680
ago, the Italian grandmother had
a very limited repertoire.

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:32.580
As I was taught to
cook by a baker--

00:33:32.580 --> 00:33:36.100
actually, a cook in Vermont--

00:33:36.100 --> 00:33:37.550
Vermont!

00:33:37.550 --> 00:33:39.310
And I have a recipe card.

00:33:39.310 --> 00:33:41.240
She has about 50 recipe cards.

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:44.340
So I think the secret has been
people had a limited

00:33:44.340 --> 00:33:48.160
repertoire of foods that were
local with techniques that

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:50.680
were all related, and that's why
they didn't need recipes.

00:33:50.680 --> 00:33:54.580
Because your grandmother, if
she cooked, or grandfather,

00:33:54.580 --> 00:33:57.250
they had a baking powder biscuit
recipe, or they had a

00:33:57.250 --> 00:33:58.290
curry goat recipe.

00:33:58.290 --> 00:34:00.160
Whatever it was, they
knew how to do it.

00:34:00.160 --> 00:34:02.010
So if you're going to start out
in cooking, and you don't

00:34:02.010 --> 00:34:06.280
have a lot of time, my
suggestion is have 25 recipes.

00:34:06.280 --> 00:34:10.570
Pick 25 recipes that cover a
braise, or a tagine, or a

00:34:10.570 --> 00:34:15.210
stew, or a quick bread, a soda
bread, whatever, and just get

00:34:15.210 --> 00:34:17.929
a range of recipes that cover
most of the bases, and get to

00:34:17.929 --> 00:34:19.060
the point you don't
need a recipe.

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:20.550
You can make them.

00:34:20.550 --> 00:34:22.060
Then you can do anything
you want.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:23.900
But if you do that, it's great,
because the problem

00:34:23.900 --> 00:34:26.239
with all of you and the problem
with me is, on Tuesday

00:34:26.239 --> 00:34:29.350
night I'm going oh, I love that
Ottolenghi recipe from

00:34:29.350 --> 00:34:31.510
"Plenty" or "Jerusalem." I want
to make that tonight with

00:34:31.510 --> 00:34:33.830
the Gorgonzola and the lentils
and the caramelized onions.

00:34:33.830 --> 00:34:35.710
And the next night, I'll say,
well, maybe I want something

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:37.449
from South America,
and then I--

00:34:37.449 --> 00:34:39.989
well, you never get anywhere,
because you're changing

00:34:39.989 --> 00:34:41.120
ingredients and techniques.

00:34:41.120 --> 00:34:43.340
So stick to 25 recipes.

00:34:43.340 --> 00:34:46.420
The example I like
to give is music.

00:34:46.420 --> 00:34:48.920
Like most aging baby
boomers, I have a

00:34:48.920 --> 00:34:49.960
Grateful Dead cover band.

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:51.469
Of course, that's typical.

00:34:51.469 --> 00:34:53.489
At some point, you all will
have Grateful Dead cover

00:34:53.489 --> 00:34:54.779
bands, or something.

00:34:54.779 --> 00:34:55.440
Aerosmith.

00:34:55.440 --> 00:34:56.550
I don't know, whatever.

00:34:56.550 --> 00:35:01.130
So if you've ever seen a
50-year-old pick up a guitar,

00:35:01.130 --> 00:35:03.760
it's a disaster because
he or she thinks they

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:04.910
can just play it--

00:35:04.910 --> 00:35:08.610
without "Guitar Hero--" play
it, and they can't, because

00:35:08.610 --> 00:35:10.090
you actually have to know
something, like there are

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:12.510
chords and scales, and there are
two note chords, and three

00:35:12.510 --> 00:35:14.680
note chords, and the triads.

00:35:14.680 --> 00:35:16.800
There's the blues scale, and
the pentatonic scale, blah,

00:35:16.800 --> 00:35:17.750
blah, blah.

00:35:17.750 --> 00:35:24.030
Jerry Garcia, my hero, he played
scales two hours a day.

00:35:24.030 --> 00:35:25.620
So there is something to know.

00:35:25.620 --> 00:35:27.790
And so by sticking to 25
recipes, you'll actually get

00:35:27.790 --> 00:35:29.230
the technique down.

00:35:29.230 --> 00:35:31.270
You'll understand something
about cooking, and then you

00:35:31.270 --> 00:35:34.210
can do whatever you
want from there.

00:35:34.210 --> 00:35:37.430
I always work Jerry Garcia into
every talk, by the way.

00:35:37.430 --> 00:35:39.160
AUDIENCE: Question about
your turkey recipes.

00:35:39.160 --> 00:35:41.710
They typically deal with
smaller birds, or

00:35:41.710 --> 00:35:42.450
medium sized birds.

00:35:42.450 --> 00:35:45.980
Do you have ideas on cooking
larger ones, particularly when

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:47.785
you're cooking them upside
down to start?

00:35:47.785 --> 00:35:50.630
Is there a limit to how big a
bird you can cook that way?

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:51.785
CHRIS KIMBALL: No.

00:35:51.785 --> 00:35:55.430
We usually like 14 to 16 pound
birds, because they, I think,

00:35:55.430 --> 00:35:56.860
usually taste better.

00:35:56.860 --> 00:35:58.140
But you can get a 22 pounder.

00:35:58.140 --> 00:35:59.910
The question is, is your
oven big enough?

00:35:59.910 --> 00:36:03.480
And then, of course, you have
a bird that's very hot, and

00:36:03.480 --> 00:36:05.400
you have to flip it over
after an hour.

00:36:05.400 --> 00:36:07.470
If you do the butterfly
technique, however, you don't

00:36:07.470 --> 00:36:08.220
have to flip it.

00:36:08.220 --> 00:36:11.050
And if you braise it in parts,
you don't have to flip it.

00:36:11.050 --> 00:36:16.630
But if you do the hour down
and then up, you do.

00:36:16.630 --> 00:36:18.620
I just use kitchen
towels to do it.

00:36:18.620 --> 00:36:21.720
Some of those Orka silicone
mitts and stuff, you ever try

00:36:21.720 --> 00:36:22.510
to use those?

00:36:22.510 --> 00:36:25.580
Your hands get sweaty,
and then you drop it

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:27.780
anyway, so who cares?

00:36:27.780 --> 00:36:32.410
So I just use kitchen
towels and flip it.

00:36:32.410 --> 00:36:32.540
