you write up recipes.

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:36.890
It's very clear from anybody
who's read "Cook's" how much

00:36:36.890 --> 00:36:38.800
work you guys put into
developing your recipes and

00:36:38.800 --> 00:36:40.150
trying out every variation.

00:36:40.150 --> 00:36:42.630
Have you had a chance to do
that with how you actually

00:36:42.630 --> 00:36:45.180
write up the recipes to present
the information and

00:36:45.180 --> 00:36:47.110
help understand what's the
best way to present it to

00:36:47.110 --> 00:36:49.014
people such that they're
able to follow it?

00:36:49.014 --> 00:36:50.264
CHRIS KIMBALL: Oh, yes.

00:36:52.350 --> 00:36:53.650
Yes.

00:36:53.650 --> 00:36:57.540
Most of the stories, because
we're dealing with cooks now,

00:36:57.540 --> 00:36:58.610
not writers--

00:36:58.610 --> 00:37:01.290
most of the people who work for
us don't have any writing

00:37:01.290 --> 00:37:06.470
experience, and so the editing
process is tortured.

00:37:06.470 --> 00:37:12.830
And we had made people cry
after reading the--

00:37:12.830 --> 00:37:14.080
I used to read everything.

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:15.460
I stopped about a year ago.

00:37:15.460 --> 00:37:17.390
I read it, but not
at the beginning.

00:37:17.390 --> 00:37:18.840
And I used to put comments in.

00:37:18.840 --> 00:37:20.660
And my comments were usually
something like, this is the

00:37:20.660 --> 00:37:23.020
worst first paragraph I've
ever read in my life.

00:37:23.020 --> 00:37:25.630
So what you get is, I remember
my mother, when she used to

00:37:25.630 --> 00:37:27.040
make-- and I'd say, look.

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:29.420
Unless you can describe your
mother in some detail and

00:37:29.420 --> 00:37:32.300
paint a picture, nobody cares
about your mother.

00:37:32.300 --> 00:37:34.140
You have to make us care.

00:37:34.140 --> 00:37:38.390
So people take a long time
to get to a point.

00:37:38.390 --> 00:37:41.380
I think the issue is, I always
say it's like a Sherlock

00:37:41.380 --> 00:37:43.710
Holmes story.

00:37:43.710 --> 00:37:46.090
There's the one boot is missing
in "The Hound of the

00:37:46.090 --> 00:37:47.340
Baskervilles," you know?

00:37:47.340 --> 00:37:51.450
So when you're telling the story
of how you solved the

00:37:51.450 --> 00:37:54.680
problem of bad food to get to
good food, it's a mystery.

00:37:54.680 --> 00:37:55.680
It's a narrative.

00:37:55.680 --> 00:37:56.940
You have to tell a story.

00:37:56.940 --> 00:37:58.720
A story has ups and downs,
it has ins and

00:37:58.720 --> 00:37:59.920
outs, it has dead ends.

00:37:59.920 --> 00:38:01.820
So you have to construct
that story.

00:38:01.820 --> 00:38:05.870
The problem is the test cook has
tested in a certain order,

00:38:05.870 --> 00:38:10.030
and he or she then thinks, it's
a documentary process of

00:38:10.030 --> 00:38:11.820
documenting what they did.

00:38:11.820 --> 00:38:12.780
That has nothing
to do with it.

00:38:12.780 --> 00:38:14.610
It's about creating a story.

00:38:14.610 --> 00:38:17.910
And so even though it doesn't
seem when you read it that

00:38:17.910 --> 00:38:21.135
we've done a lot of work, we
spend some time, it's like 50

00:38:21.135 --> 00:38:25.800
or 60 hours on the story, to
tell a story, because people

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:26.830
have to care about the story.

00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:30.100
Who wants to read 2,000 words
about fudgy brownies unless

00:38:30.100 --> 00:38:31.640
you kind of make
it interesting?

00:38:31.640 --> 00:38:33.530
And so a lot of the tests
we leave out.

00:38:33.530 --> 00:38:35.250
It's like editing a
Hollywood movie.

00:38:35.250 --> 00:38:37.480
You've got to cut characters
out and scenes.

00:38:37.480 --> 00:38:38.140
It's the same thing.

00:38:38.140 --> 00:38:40.170
So it's all about storytelling
and narrative.

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:43.730
And then finally, we call it
the aha moment, when you

00:38:43.730 --> 00:38:47.610
finally, what's the big thing
you discovered that made the

00:38:47.610 --> 00:38:48.350
recipe work?

00:38:48.350 --> 00:38:49.770
And hopefully there's something
interesting.

00:38:53.590 --> 00:38:54.940
AUDIENCE: When you were talking
about cooking myths

00:38:54.940 --> 00:38:57.840
and how they're not true, you
mentioned searing the meat,

00:38:57.840 --> 00:39:00.710
which we've heard from Harold
McGee a couple times.

00:39:00.710 --> 00:39:02.860
But you also mentioned
patting the meat try

00:39:02.860 --> 00:39:04.300
before you sautee it.

00:39:04.300 --> 00:39:08.170
And I don't think you followed
through on why that's a myth.

00:39:08.170 --> 00:39:16.460
CHRIS KIMBALL: Well, what I
said was, it's not a myth.

00:39:16.460 --> 00:39:19.130
It's something that people tell
you to do, but people

00:39:19.130 --> 00:39:20.770
don't do it, because they don't
understand why they

00:39:20.770 --> 00:39:22.280
should do it.

00:39:22.280 --> 00:39:25.115
And the reason is, as I said,
if you put the meat in a pan

00:39:25.115 --> 00:39:29.570
and it's wet, until the water
turns to steam and evaporates,

00:39:29.570 --> 00:39:31.950
the surface temperature of the
meat's not going to go over

00:39:31.950 --> 00:39:34.120
the boiling point of water.

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:36.320
So all that energy's going
into the water to

00:39:36.320 --> 00:39:37.780
turn it into steam.

00:39:37.780 --> 00:39:39.320
The energy is not going
into the meat.

00:39:39.320 --> 00:39:41.760
So until that happens, you're
sitting there in the pan with

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:43.440
a fairly cool pan.

00:39:43.440 --> 00:39:45.490
You're not getting any browning,
you're not getting

00:39:45.490 --> 00:39:46.660
any Maillard reaction.

00:39:46.660 --> 00:39:51.455
So that's one of those things
you need to do.

00:39:51.455 --> 00:39:55.700
What I've discovered is people
won't do what recipes tell you

00:39:55.700 --> 00:39:57.530
unless you understand it.

00:39:57.530 --> 00:39:58.780
And that was my problem, too.

00:39:58.780 --> 00:40:01.055
So we're just trying to explain
in some cases not

00:40:01.055 --> 00:40:02.730
necessarily a myth, but we're
trying to explain why you

00:40:02.730 --> 00:40:05.355
should do it, and the odds of
you doing it will be greater

00:40:05.355 --> 00:40:07.176
if we explain it.

00:40:07.176 --> 00:40:09.280
AUDIENCE: It's not because the
water will spatter in the oil

00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:10.810
and get you burned?

00:40:10.810 --> 00:40:13.160
CHRIS KIMBALL: That would
be true, too, and yes.

00:40:13.160 --> 00:40:16.210
And the other thing is that if
it's wet, the chicken skin

00:40:16.210 --> 00:40:18.565
will stick irretrievably
to the bottom of

00:40:18.565 --> 00:40:20.157
the skillet, yes.

00:40:20.157 --> 00:40:21.290
AUDIENCE: Hi.

