00:43:52.410 --> 00:43:54.690
And home cooking hasn't
changed much, really.

00:43:54.690 --> 00:43:58.300
It's starting to, in
the last two years.

00:43:58.300 --> 00:44:00.490
Nothing goes into our magazines
unless we survey it.

00:44:00.490 --> 00:44:02.200
We ask you what you want.

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:03.690
It's that old story.

00:44:03.690 --> 00:44:07.695
In 1985, I was owned in part by
"The New Yorker." And so I

00:44:07.695 --> 00:44:09.300
had an office at "The
New Yorker's"

00:44:09.300 --> 00:44:10.830
building, and Bill Shawn--

00:44:10.830 --> 00:44:12.380
William Shawn was the
editor back then, as

00:44:12.380 --> 00:44:13.630
some of you may remember.

00:44:13.630 --> 00:44:16.400
And Si Newhouse took Mr. Shawn
out for lunch at the Four

00:44:16.400 --> 00:44:19.320
Seasons and said, Mr. Shawn, how
do you determine what your

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:20.900
readers want to read?

00:44:20.900 --> 00:44:23.420
And Mr. Shawn said, I don't.

00:44:23.420 --> 00:44:25.330
And Mr. Newhouse said,
what do you mean?

00:44:25.330 --> 00:44:27.670
And he said, well, I just put
things in the magazine that I

00:44:27.670 --> 00:44:30.650
want to read, and I assume
my readers have the

00:44:30.650 --> 00:44:32.040
same tastes I do.

00:44:32.040 --> 00:44:34.430
He was fired four
months later.

00:44:34.430 --> 00:44:38.310
And my answer to that is we
only put things in the

00:44:38.310 --> 00:44:41.700
magazine that you tell us you
want, because we don't take

00:44:41.700 --> 00:44:42.800
advertising.

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:45.030
So we found in the last two
years that what you want is

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:45.880
starting to change.

00:44:45.880 --> 00:44:49.090
That being said, I have
to say two things.

00:44:49.090 --> 00:44:52.610
The top 10 rated recipes of all
time out of 7,000 recipes

00:44:52.610 --> 00:44:55.310
we've rated-- we rate
every week--

00:44:55.310 --> 00:44:57.298
two of them are green
bean casserole.

00:44:57.298 --> 00:45:00.290
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:45:00.290 --> 00:45:02.440
CHRIS KIMBALL: Somebody here
makes green bean casserole.

00:45:02.440 --> 00:45:05.670
Statistically, it
has to be true.

00:45:05.670 --> 00:45:08.190
I don't know why, but they do.

00:45:08.190 --> 00:45:14.270
And so what's starting to happen
now is techniques-- not

00:45:14.270 --> 00:45:15.400
necessarily science,
but techniques--

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:19.660
I mean, stir fry used to be
ethnic at one time, right?

00:45:19.660 --> 00:45:21.750
Which is ridiculous,
but it makes sense.

00:45:21.750 --> 00:45:23.950
Small pieces of food cook
really quickly.

00:45:23.950 --> 00:45:26.010
It's very variable.

00:45:26.010 --> 00:45:29.100
It got incorporated into the
American repertoire fast.

00:45:29.100 --> 00:45:32.200
Now all the things coming from
different parts of the world

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:33.980
that do make sense for American
home cooking, and

00:45:33.980 --> 00:45:35.210
they are coming in.

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:37.260
And I would think in the next
five to eight years, you'll

00:45:37.260 --> 00:45:39.210
see a huge change in American
home cooking.

00:45:39.210 --> 00:45:42.190
It's just starting, but it
hasn't happened yet.

00:45:42.190 --> 00:45:47.030
People are still making that
dried out lasagna, but that's

00:45:47.030 --> 00:45:47.610
really changing.

00:45:47.610 --> 00:45:50.020
I would suggest that my favorite
book currently is

00:45:50.020 --> 00:45:55.100
Ottolenghi's "Plenty." I just
got "Jeruslaem." I've tried a

00:45:55.100 --> 00:45:55.570
couple things.

00:45:55.570 --> 00:45:58.280
I've cooked about half of the
recipes in that, because, you

00:45:58.280 --> 00:46:02.540
know, the Ottoman Empire was
in the spice trade, on the

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:04.040
spice routes.

00:46:04.040 --> 00:46:06.530
They had 85 to 90 different
spices.

00:46:06.530 --> 00:46:08.680
Northern Europe had
a dozen spices.

00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:11.400
"The Joy of Cooking" originally
had 15 spices.

00:46:11.400 --> 00:46:15.480
So there are ways of combining
flavors, there are techniques

00:46:15.480 --> 00:46:18.180
that we have never used here,
because we're mostly northern

00:46:18.180 --> 00:46:20.630
European style cooking,
mostly.

00:46:20.630 --> 00:46:22.140
And there's a lot that's
going to come in.

00:46:22.140 --> 00:46:24.420
So I think it's going to change
completely, and I think

00:46:24.420 --> 00:46:26.810
people's experience
with food through

00:46:26.810 --> 00:46:29.270
restaurants has also changed.

00:46:29.270 --> 00:46:31.870
They know what saag
paneer is now.

00:46:31.870 --> 00:46:34.950
I still don't want to make it at
home, but many people in my

00:46:34.950 --> 00:46:36.100
kitchen do.

00:46:36.100 --> 00:46:37.860
But no, it's going to change.

00:46:41.550 --> 00:46:44.500
AUDIENCE: So at the beginning
of your articles, you have

00:46:44.500 --> 00:46:46.450
this description of what
you're going for.

00:46:46.450 --> 00:46:48.580
We want a tender crust
or whatever.

00:46:48.580 --> 00:46:53.310
So where does that preference
come from?

00:46:53.310 --> 00:46:56.025
CHRIS KIMBALL: Well, the
question is, we have to pick a

00:46:56.025 --> 00:46:57.590
lane for a story.

00:46:57.590 --> 00:47:01.000
And so we survey and ask
what people want.

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:04.180
But at some point, it depends
on what we've done before.

00:47:04.180 --> 00:47:06.860
We have to come to it with a
different point of view.

00:47:06.860 --> 00:47:09.400
But you can do chewy chocolate
chip cookies, or you can do

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:13.370
crispy chocolate chip cookies,
and one's not

00:47:13.370 --> 00:47:15.490
better than the other.

00:47:15.490 --> 00:47:18.960
So it's mostly what you say, and
it's also our tastes, and

00:47:18.960 --> 00:47:20.840
whether we think we can
add some value,

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:21.890
because it's a new direction.

00:47:21.890 --> 00:47:23.760
It's something different.

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:27.410
Sometimes we'll go back and do
a story we did 10 years ago,

00:47:27.410 --> 00:47:29.410
because we found out actually
it's not as good as it should

00:47:29.410 --> 00:47:32.030
be, like pumpkin pie,
or creme brulee.

00:47:32.030 --> 00:47:33.910
But it's mostly just a function
of listening to what

00:47:33.910 --> 00:47:36.750
you guys want.

00:47:36.750 --> 00:47:40.870
AUDIENCE: OK, sorry, one more,
since I'm a new cook.

00:47:40.870 --> 00:47:44.650
So the trouble I always have
is doubling recipes.

00:47:44.650 --> 00:47:47.740
I always assume that if I need
to double it for whatever

00:47:47.740 --> 00:47:49.940
reason, like a sauce or
whatever, that I literally

00:47:49.940 --> 00:47:54.700
double every single ingredient
I see, which, yeah, OK.

00:47:54.700 --> 00:47:57.280
So are there certain things,
or a key, or something you

00:47:57.280 --> 00:48:01.030
should use like never double
your flour, or only do that

00:48:01.030 --> 00:48:03.360
amount and a quarter
or something?

00:48:03.360 --> 00:48:05.140
CHRIS KIMBALL: Savory
versus baking.

00:48:05.140 --> 00:48:07.570
Savory, a few things
to watch out for.

00:48:07.570 --> 00:48:09.890
Don't double the heat
or the spices.

00:48:09.890 --> 00:48:11.080
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:48:11.080 --> 00:48:13.850
CHRIS KIMBALL: Because
you hold off and then

00:48:13.850 --> 00:48:14.830
taste as you go.

00:48:14.830 --> 00:48:15.980
But that's really a problem.

00:48:15.980 --> 00:48:17.000
Secondly, liquid.

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.640
Sometimes in a stew, if you're
going to triple a stew, you

00:48:19.640 --> 00:48:21.130
don't need triple the liquid.

00:48:21.130 --> 00:48:23.590
So that's something you
should look at.

00:48:23.590 --> 00:48:27.680
The other thing is in baking,
as you double a recipe, then

00:48:27.680 --> 00:48:29.670
the pan size doesn't
necessarily-- you need a

00:48:29.670 --> 00:48:31.100
different pan size.

00:48:31.100 --> 00:48:34.550
And you may end up with a
thicker, or more depth to the

00:48:34.550 --> 00:48:36.670
cake, or whatever you're doing,
so the cooking time's

00:48:36.670 --> 00:48:38.070
going to be off.

00:48:38.070 --> 00:48:40.090
If you're going to create
something bigger, you tend to

00:48:40.090 --> 00:48:43.630
lower the oven temperature by
25 degrees, so it's going to

00:48:43.630 --> 00:48:45.140
have to cook a little
longer, so you don't

00:48:45.140 --> 00:48:46.480
overcook the outside.

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:48.410
In general, baking is tough.

00:48:48.410 --> 00:48:51.860
And also, when you mix things
together, like you're creaming

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:54.110
butter or mixing things
together, if you quadruple a

00:48:54.110 --> 00:48:57.380
recipe, when you mix it, you're
going to over mix it to

00:48:57.380 --> 00:48:58.700
get everything mixed together.

00:48:58.700 --> 00:49:01.360
For example, when you make
brownies, it always says, or

00:49:01.360 --> 00:49:06.600
should say, streaks of flour
left in the batter?

00:49:06.600 --> 00:49:08.370
Well, I know what you do,
because I do the same thing.

00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:09.560
I'm going like, hey, there
are still streaks of

00:49:09.560 --> 00:49:10.250
flour in the batter.

00:49:10.250 --> 00:49:11.190
This can't be right.

00:49:11.190 --> 00:49:13.570
So you keep going
a couple more.

00:49:13.570 --> 00:49:16.280
Well, what happens is you
develop gluten as a result.

00:49:16.280 --> 00:49:18.640
The brownies rise a little bit
more, because there's more

00:49:18.640 --> 00:49:20.540
structure, but they
turn out cakey.

00:49:20.540 --> 00:49:21.650
Not that good.

00:49:21.650 --> 00:49:23.630
So when you have double the
recipe or quadruple the

00:49:23.630 --> 00:49:26.310
recipe, you end up mixing more,
there's more agitation,

00:49:26.310 --> 00:49:27.570
and you end up--

00:49:27.570 --> 00:49:31.380
so very often in the test
kitchen, we'll just maybe

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:34.962
double it, maybe not, and just
make more than one batch.

00:49:34.962 --> 00:49:36.940
But baking is particularly
difficult.

00:49:36.940 --> 00:49:38.924
AUDIENCE: So what about
cider-braised pork steaks,

00:49:38.924 --> 00:49:40.620
like a recipe like that?

00:49:40.620 --> 00:49:41.412
CHRIS KIMBALL: That's
not a problem.

00:49:41.412 --> 00:49:43.260
AUDIENCE: You can double that?

00:49:43.260 --> 00:49:45.830
CHRIS KIMBALL: Yeah.

00:49:45.830 --> 00:49:48.640
AUDIENCE: In the magazine where
the people write in with

00:49:48.640 --> 00:49:51.960
questions, there was once
a question about using

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:54.830
California bay laurel leaves
instead of [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:54.830 --> 00:49:55.800
CHRIS KIMBALL: Oh
yeah, Turkish.

00:49:55.800 --> 00:49:56.070
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:49:56.070 --> 00:50:01.150
And the answer was that it
wasn't worth the price to use

00:50:01.150 --> 00:50:02.000
California.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:03.750
But the thing is that we're
here in California.

00:50:03.750 --> 00:50:05.310
A lot of people have those
trees in their

00:50:05.310 --> 00:50:06.710
yard, so it's free.

00:50:06.710 --> 00:50:10.930
And so I was wondering, can
you use the bay that grows

00:50:10.930 --> 00:50:15.210
around here, and do you use a
different amount, or is it

00:50:15.210 --> 00:50:16.220
just one for--

00:50:16.220 --> 00:50:17.340
CHRIS KIMBALL: I do remember
that letter.

00:50:17.340 --> 00:50:17.830
It was a few years ago.

00:50:17.830 --> 00:50:20.860
I think we decided that we
preferred, actually, the

00:50:20.860 --> 00:50:22.070
California, I think.

00:50:22.070 --> 00:50:23.450
But yeah, sure.

00:50:23.450 --> 00:50:23.900
You can use them.

00:50:23.900 --> 00:50:28.095
I mean, my pet peeve is-- and
I argue this all the time--

00:50:28.095 --> 00:50:31.280
you know recipes, you're doing
a stew for 12 people, and it

00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:33.310
says add a sprig of thyme?

00:50:33.310 --> 00:50:34.930
Are you kidding me?

00:50:34.930 --> 00:50:36.690
I mean, I don't know, maybe the
French had particularly

00:50:36.690 --> 00:50:37.790
pungent thyme.

00:50:37.790 --> 00:50:40.910
But I mean, a sprig of thyme
isn't going to do anything.

00:50:40.910 --> 00:50:42.520
You're never going to
know it's there.

00:50:42.520 --> 00:50:45.020
And sometimes I feel the same
way about bay leaves--

00:50:45.020 --> 00:50:46.020
I always add an extra one.

00:50:46.020 --> 00:50:47.560
So yeah, you can use it, sure.

00:50:47.560 --> 00:50:52.690
But I think one thing I've
learned is, also, towards the

00:50:52.690 --> 00:50:56.280
end of cooking, I mean, unless
it's baking, but if it's a

00:50:56.280 --> 00:50:59.220
stew, a soup, or whatever,
taste it.

00:50:59.220 --> 00:51:01.310
People just assume--

00:51:01.310 --> 00:51:02.770
my 22-year-old loves to cook--

00:51:02.770 --> 00:51:05.170
and she'll just follow the
recipe and won't taste

00:51:05.170 --> 00:51:06.260
it and serve it.

00:51:06.260 --> 00:51:08.095
And, you know, it needs salt,
it needs something else, a

00:51:08.095 --> 00:51:09.360
little vinegar.

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:11.920
But at the end of cooking, fresh
herbs are best added at

00:51:11.920 --> 00:51:18.030
the end, grated or minced
ginger, garlic.

00:51:18.030 --> 00:51:19.790
There's lots of little things
you can add at the end of

00:51:19.790 --> 00:51:21.900
cooking-- vinegar,
lemon juice--

00:51:21.900 --> 00:51:23.550
to get the balance right.

00:51:23.550 --> 00:51:26.370
And so that's the most important
part of cooking,

00:51:26.370 --> 00:51:29.580
other than cleaning up, is
the last five minutes.

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:31.820
And adding those things
at the end.

00:51:31.820 --> 00:51:34.330
And there's also secret
ingredients.

00:51:34.330 --> 00:51:37.270
Years ago, someone in my office
mentioned pomegranate

00:51:37.270 --> 00:51:39.620
molasses, and I made fun of
them, because it's a stupid

00:51:39.620 --> 00:51:40.400
hard to find ingredient.

00:51:40.400 --> 00:51:41.930
Now it's not hard to find.

00:51:41.930 --> 00:51:44.440
That's one of the things I have
at my disposal when I'm

00:51:44.440 --> 00:51:46.530
cooking, just to get
the balance right.

00:51:46.530 --> 00:51:48.880
It's a little sweet,
a little sour.

00:51:48.880 --> 00:51:51.850
So it's that last minute that's
really important.

00:51:51.850 --> 00:51:54.140
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned about
thinking that there's

00:51:54.140 --> 00:51:58.550
new spices, and that kind
of thing, maybe some new

00:51:58.550 --> 00:52:01.338
techniques coming from
around the world.

00:52:01.338 --> 00:52:06.070
What about just new approaches,
and I guess more

00:52:06.070 --> 00:52:09.600
technology in the kitchen?

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:11.550
CHRIS KIMBALL: Well,
sure, yes.

00:52:11.550 --> 00:52:15.650
We're doing a pressure cooker
book right now.

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:19.190
That's actually going to be
huge, because it's fast.

00:52:19.190 --> 00:52:21.870
It's not a slow cooker,
it's a fast cooker.

00:52:21.870 --> 00:52:24.590
You can make the world's best
chicken stock in 15 minutes.

00:52:24.590 --> 00:52:26.420
You can make risotto
in 15 minutes.

00:52:26.420 --> 00:52:28.840
And also, a pressure cooker
turns out great food.

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:31.050
So that's going to be big.

00:52:31.050 --> 00:52:33.890
Everyone's talking
about sous-vide.

00:52:33.890 --> 00:52:36.330
AUDIENCE: That's getting
to be affordable now.

00:52:36.330 --> 00:52:40.400
CHRIS KIMBALL: There's a $450
one we liked, which is--

00:52:40.400 --> 00:52:43.210
I mean, the problem with that
is, money is one issue, but

00:52:43.210 --> 00:52:44.850
then what do you do with it?

00:52:44.850 --> 00:52:48.230
I'm sorry, I've gotten down to
small things now, because

00:52:48.230 --> 00:52:51.150
these big things, you've
got to take it out.

00:52:51.150 --> 00:52:52.660
But yeah, sous-vide is fine.

00:52:52.660 --> 00:52:55.410
Although, I have to say, the
problem with sous-vide for me

00:52:55.410 --> 00:52:58.610
is I like to chew my food.

00:52:58.610 --> 00:53:01.900
And I find, like, if you've
ever had a turkey sandwich

00:53:01.900 --> 00:53:06.420
made with sous-vide turkey,
it feels kind of wet.

00:53:06.420 --> 00:53:09.510
And so as a friend of mine
said about turkey at

00:53:09.510 --> 00:53:14.150
Thanksgiving, he says he likes
overcooked white meat, because

00:53:14.150 --> 00:53:15.740
that's the tradition
at his house.

00:53:15.740 --> 00:53:17.590
And he said that's why
God invented gravy.

00:53:17.590 --> 00:53:18.190
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:53:18.190 --> 00:53:21.180
CHRIS KIMBALL: Well, who wants
gravy and a particularly moist

00:53:21.180 --> 00:53:21.900
piece of white meat?

00:53:21.900 --> 00:53:22.960
It doesn't work.

00:53:22.960 --> 00:53:24.630
So I don't know.

00:53:24.630 --> 00:53:27.480
Yeah, it's a great way of
cooking, but I don't think

00:53:27.480 --> 00:53:28.740
that's going to be in
everybody's kitchen.

00:53:28.740 --> 00:53:30.360
But I think the pressure cooker
is probably one of

00:53:30.360 --> 00:53:31.490
those things that will be.

00:53:31.490 --> 00:53:32.990
So thank you very much.

00:53:32.990 --> 00:53:37.032
[APPLAUSE]

